  "prompt": "Complete an orbital diagram for scandium (Sc).?",
  "response": "To complete an orbital diagram for scandium (Sc), which has an atomic number of 21, you'll need to distribute the 21 electrons among the available atomic orbitals according to the principles of electron configuration: the Aufbau principle, the Pauli exclusion principle, and Hund's rule. Here's the step-by-step breakdown:\n\n1. **Identify the order of orbital filling:**\n   - Orbitals fill in the order of increasing energy, which generally follows the sequence: 1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p, 4s, 3d, 4p, etc.\n\n2. **Fill the orbitals with electrons:**\n   - The maximum number of electrons that can occupy an orbital is:\n     - s subshell: 2 electrons\n     - p subshell: 6 electrons\n     - d subshell: 10 electrons\n\n3. **Scandium has 21 electrons:**\n\n- **1s^2**: Two electrons fill the 1s orbital.\n- **2s^2**: Two electrons fill the 2s orbital.\n- **2p^6**: Six electrons fill the 2p orbitals (px, py, pz).\n- **3s^2**: Two electrons fill the 3s orbital.\n- **3p^6**: Six electrons fill the 3p orbitals (px, py, pz).\n- **4s^2**: Two electrons fill the 4s orbital.\n- **3d^1**: One electron fills one of the 3d orbitals.\n\n4. **Orbital Diagram:**\n\n```\n1s:  \u2191\u2193\n2s:  \u2191\u2193\n2p:  \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193\n3s:  \u2191\u2193\n3p:  \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193 \u2191\u2193\n4s:  \u2191\u2193\n3d:  \u2191 _ _ _ _\n```\n\n- Arrows indicate electrons; their direction (up or down) reflects the electron spin. Each orbital holds a maximum of two electrons with opposite spins (according to the Pauli exclusion principle).\n- Notice in the 3d subshell, only one of the five orbitals is singly occupied, consistent with Hund's rule, where each orbital in a subshell is singly filled before any orbital is doubly filled.\n\nThis orbital diagram successfully represents the electron configuration for scandium.",
